{"timestamp": "2025-12-02 14:49:04.065856", "event": "llm_end", "text": "Troubleshooting diagnosis report\nGoal: assess network health, detect anomalies, localize faulty devices and identify probable root cause(s). Tools used: reachability matrix, host network configs, ethtool, ping tests, neighbor/ARP inspection on distribution router and access switch.\n\nExecutive summary\n- Overall the network is largely healthy: most user hosts (10.<core>.<dist>.0/24) can reach DNS, DHCP, the load‑balancer and the published web frontends in 10.200.0.0/24 with low/normal latencies. OSPF/FRR routing appears to be propagating server and infrastructure prefixes correctly for the majority of endpoints.\n- One clear anomaly: host_2_1_1_1 (10.2.1.10) exhibits loss of two‑way connectivity to the rest of the network. The problem is localized to layer‑2/neighbor resolution between that host and its distribution/access side. Other hosts in the same subnet (10.2.1.11–13) are reachable, so the issue is specific to the host or its immediate switch port, not the distribution/router fabric.\n- The \"unknown\" reachability results seen to addresses in 20.200.0.0/24 (backend_web_0..2) from hosts are consistent with the design that backend web servers are intentionally not directly reachable from hosts; those are expected and not treated as a fault.\n\nScope of tests performed\n- Full reachability matrix (ping all hosts → results analyzed).\n- Collected network config (ifconfig / ip addr / ip route) for host_2_1_1_1 and router_dist_2_1.\n- ethtool on host_2_1_1_1.\n- ping from router_dist_2_1 → host_2_1_1_1.\n- ip neigh (ARP table) on router_dist_2_1 and host_2_1_1_1.\n- ifconfig/ip addr for switch_access_2_1_1.\n\nKey findings and evidence\n1) Global (network-wide) health\n   - Most hosts (across cores/ distribution routers) can ping:\n     - DNS server 10.200.0.2, DHCP 10.200.0.8, load_balancer 10.200.0.7 and web frontends 10.200.0.3–6 — results show 0% loss and reasonable RTTs.\n   - Inter-server connectivity within 10.200.0.0/24 is healthy; backend servers and load balancer show low RTTs between themselves.\n   - OSPF/FRR routing appears to be functioning for advertised prefixes (hosts can resolve and reach published services).\n\n2) Localized problem: host_2_1_1_1 (10.2.1.10)\n   - Host config (host_2_1_1_1):\n     - ifconfig: eth0 configured 10.2.1.10/24, interface UP.\n     - ip route: default via 10.2.1.1 dev eth0 (gateway = router_dist_2_1).\n     - ethtool: Link detected: yes (10Gbps, full duplex; auto-neg off).\n     - ARP table/neighbor on host: empty (no learned neighbors shown; /proc/net/arp empty).\n     - Packet counters: RX packets 137, TX packets only 25 (low TX).\n   - Distribution router (router_dist_2_1) observations:\n     - br0 configured 10.2.1.1/24, br0 is UP and other hosts on same subnet are reachable.\n     - ip neigh (ARP) shows: \"10.2.1.10 dev br0 FAILED\" — i.e. the router attempted ARP resolution but the neighbor is unresolved/failed.\n     - ping from router_dist_2_1 to 10.2.1.10 produced: \"From 10.2.1.1 ... Destination Host Unreachable\" for all probes.\n   - Access switch (switch_access_2_1_1) observations:\n     - Bridge br0 and member interfaces are UP.\n     - Interface counters show limited packet counts on the access port toward hosts (eth1 RX 26 bytes, TX 157 bytes) — some traffic present but small.\n     - ip neigh output on switch was empty (switch not showing host neighbor).\n\n3) Expected isolation of backend IPs\n   - Many hosts report \"unknown\" for pings to backend_web_* (20.200.0.x). This matches design (backend web servers should not be directly accessible from hosts), so that is not an unexpected failure.\n\nAnomaly summary (what is abnormal)\n- host_2_1_1_1 (10.2.1.10) is unreachable from its distribution router and cannot successfully complete neighbor (ARP) exchange with the router:\n  - Router ARP shows neighbor FAILED for 10.2.1.10.\n  - Router ping returns Destination Host Unreachable.\n  - Host has interface up and IP assigned but appears not to be replying to ARP or not transmitting at L2 (host ARP table empty; very low TX count).\n- All other subnets/hosts and server farm are reachable and show healthy performance; problem is isolated.\n\nLocalization — probable faulty device(s)\n- Primary suspect: host_2_1_1_1 itself (NIC/OS/network stack) — symptom: interface reports link up, but lack of ARP responses / minimal TX.\n- Secondary suspect: the immediate access switch port or its configuration (switch_access_2_1_1 → port connected to host_2_1_1_1). Evidence: router sees neighbor FAILED, switch port counters are small (some traffic but limited). Because the switch and router see other hosts OK, a misconfiguration or per‑port issue (VLAN, port isolation, or MAC learning suppression) on this specific access port is possible.\n- Unlikely: upstream routing/core or OSPF — other hosts in the same subnet and beyond are reachable; distribution router and downstream networks are functioning.\n\nProbable root cause(s) (ranked)\n1) Host NIC / host OS problem preventing ARP replies or transmission (e.g., host firewall blocking ARP/ICMP, NIC in an odd state, wrong MAC, driver issue, or misconfigured IP on a different interface). Evidence: host eth0 up and has IP, but ARP table empty and TX counters low; ethtool shows link presence but no ARP replies observed by router.\n2) Access switch port problem (VLAN mismatch, port administratively up but MAC learning suppressed, port security blocking the host MAC, or spanning-tree state preventing forwarding for that port). Evidence: switch shows small packet counters on relevant port and the router sees the neighbor as FAILED while other hosts on same switch/subnet are ok.\n3) Physical layer flakiness (cable, SFP) — less likely because ethtool shows link detected and host link speed present, but intermittent or asymmetric signal could cause lack of ARP responses.\n4) Less likely items: a duplicate IP/MAC conflict elsewhere (would normally show different symptoms, e.g., ARP flips or intermittent reachability). No evidence of duplicate IPs in router's neighbor list.\n\nImpact\n- host_2_1_1_1 cannot communicate with DHCP/DNS/servers or other hosts — effectively isolated.\n- No broader network degradation observed; services and other hosts unaffected.\n\nRelevant command outputs (paraphrased evidence)\n- router_dist_2_1 ip neigh: \"10.2.1.10 dev br0 FAILED\" (ARP unresolved).\n- router_dist_2_1 → ping 10.2.1.10: \"Destination Host Unreachable\".\n- host_2_1_1_1 ifconfig/ip addr: eth0 = 10.2.1.10/24, interface UP.\n- host_2_1_1_1 ethtool: Link detected: yes.\n- host_2_1_1_1 ip neigh / /proc/net/arp: no entries / empty.\n- switch_access_2_1_1: bridge and interfaces up; low counters for the access port.\n\nSuggested next diagnostic data to collect (if you want to continue investigation)\n(These are suggestions of further evidence collection — not mitigation steps)\n- On the access switch: show mac address table / show interface status for the port connecting to host_2_1_1_1; look for port security blocks, VLAN membership, STP state.\n- On the host: verify ARP behavior while generating traffic (run arp requests/arping, tcpdump/pcap on eth0 to see if ARP requests are sent and whether replies are transmitted), check firewall (iptables/nft) and link state logs, check dmesg for NIC driver errors.\n- On the distribution router: capture packets on br0 while attempting ARP to 10.2.1.10 to observe ARP traffic and any replies.\n- Physical check: cable / port reseat or swap with a known good host port to rule out hardware.\n\nConclusion\n- The network and OSPF routing are healthy overall; the server farm and published web services are reachable from hosts.\n- The only abnormal behavior is isolation of host_2_1_1_1 (10.2.1.10). Evidence points to a layer‑2 neighbor resolution failure between that host and the access/distribution switch (host not replying to ARP). Root cause is likely local to the host NIC or the immediate access switch port (host OS/driver/config or port/VLAN/port‑security issue).", "generation_info": {"finish_reason": "stop", "logprobs": null}, "invalid_tool_calls": [], "usage_metadata": {"input_tokens": 37479, "output_tokens": 4009, "total_tokens": 41488, "input_token_details": {"audio": 0, "cache_read": 36608}, "output_token_details": {"audio": 0, "reasoning": 1984}}}
